p2
VReverberating with Rama bhakti
p3
sVnews
p4
VVijayalakshmi Subramaniam's wholesome fare suffused with a lambent flow of phrases showcased her nuances of raga alapanas, niraval and swaras in her refined vocal concert at the Thyagabrahma aradhana celebrations of Thyagabrahma Gananjali in the precincts of Sree Venugopalaswami temple, on Sullivan street in Coimbatore.Her upbeat commencement with &#8216;Inthanuchu' (Guntakria) was followed by an unhurried elaboration of Nattai for the kriti, &#8216;Ninnebhajana' embellished with swaras.Long korvais, striking sancharas and sangatis formed her raga edifice for the kriti, &#8216;Kandajutumu.' She rendered Tyagaraja's &#8216;Nannuvidachi' in Ritigowla with bhava. The piece-de-resistance of the concert was the Thodi raga vinyasam for the kriti, &#8216;Koluvamaragada.'&#8216;Iti Samayamura' (Chalanata) was presented with passionate grace. Murari's violin support was classy and his solo versions of Thodi and Ritigowla stood out for the spate of their sancharas.Balaji (mridangam) and Subramanian (ganjira) brought out the dignity of their percussive support. Earlier the function was inaugurated by K. Nageshwar Rao, Chief Commissioner of Income tax, Coimbatore.Aural treatTonal eloquence coupled with their vidwat and manodharma, the kutcheri of the Mallari duo on the second day of the aradhana was an aural treat for rasikas.The rendition of &#8216;Epaniko' (Asaveri) where the bard tells the purpose of his life is to sing the glory of Lord Rama with faith and devotion set the tone for a melodious session.Ramkumar's alapana of Vasantha for the kriti, &#8216;Etladorigithi' was a linear development interspersed with swift flashes through the sthayis.Ravikumar's delineation of Ramapriya for the kriti, &#8216;Sandehamu' with traditional pidis were pieced together with minute embellishments.Clarity of diction, perfect alignment to sruti and laya accuracy were the hallmarks of the recital.Vittal Ramamurthi imparted deft touches and delicate shades in the raga expansions.Vaidyanathan's (mridangam) thani in the company of Mohanram (ghatam) bore testimony to their laya expertise.
